nted the required detailed display logic in the `final` block. This includes displaying the input signals (`a` through `e`) and the DUT/Expected outputs (`out_dut`, `out_ref`) at the first mismatch time, using the `display_vector` task to show both HEX and BINARY formats for multi-bit signals.\\n*   **Reporting Logic:** The final block now strictly adheres to the requirement: display "  ,  " if `stats1.errors == 0`, or display the specific failure message: \\"SIMULATION FAILED - x MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME y\\" if errors exist.\\n*   **Functionality Preservation:** Maintained the original error counting logic (`stats1.errors`, `stats1.errortime`) and the compatibility logic (`stats1.errors_out`, `stats1.errortime_out`) from the golden testbench.\\n*   **Port Mapping:** Ensured all module instantiations use named association (`.port(signal)`) to prevent the positional errors seen in the logs, following the robust style of the previous TB.\\n\\n**Advice to Avoid Syntax Errors:**\\n1.  **Quoting:** Always ensure strings passed to `$display` or `$monitor` are properly enclosed with double quotes (`\\"`). Missing quotes are a common source of \'Malformed statement\' errors.\\n2.  **Instance Syntax:** When instantiating modules, use named port association (`.input_name(signal_name)`) instead of relying purely on positional mapping when mixing standard and keyword styles, as this makes the code resilient to port reordering changes.\\n3.  **Variable Naming:** Double-check variable names, especially when copying code (e.g., checking for typos like `sstats1` vs `stats1`).\\n4.  **Module Closure:** Ensure every `module` starts with `module Name (...)` and ends with `endmodule`.\\n\\nThis results in a fully corrected and enhanced testbench that meets all specified criteria, including the exact interface required by the TB structure."\n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    